entry.title: Pass the histogram shared memory region on child process launch.
entry.content:
This CL, behind a flag, updates the create/share flow for the histogram shared memory region between the browser process and its child processes. This allows the child processes to immediately allocate metrics from the shared memory region instead of waiting until the first browser/child IPC.



For the renderer, the shared memory region and allocator are created before the child is launched. This was already the case for the other child processes.



In the browser, the child process hosts expose the shared memory region to the ChildProcessLauncher/Helper so that the handle to the shared memory region passed to the child process on launch.



In the child, the metrics service initializes its histogram allocator to use the shared memory, on seeing the --histogram-shared-memory-region parameter.



See:



* go/improve-chrome-subprocess-metrics



Bug: 1028263, 1290457

entry.title: Add serializable attribute to shadow roots, and prep for setHTML [1/2]
entry.content:
This CL adds a `serializable` bool to ShadowRoot, and makes it available

to set via `attachShadow()` plus read/write via an IDL attribute. This

also adds a content attribute `serializable` on `HTMLTemplateElement`

and a corresponding reflection. The `serializable` state will be tested

as part of the next CL which implements `getHTML()` and uses

`serializable`.



This CL also takes the opportunity to do a few other things to prepare

for `getHTML()`:

1. Add a feature flag `ElementGetHTML` which will gate the new function

and which also gates the `serializable` changes above.

2. Add a feature flag `ElementGetInnerHTML` which is default-"stable"

and will gate the getInnerHTML() function (mostly in the next CL).

3. Rename `IncludeShadowRoots` as used in *set* methods to

`ParseDeclarativeShadowRoots` to better represent what it means,

and also to disambiguate it from some of the `getInnerHTML`

parameters, which are unrelated. These names refer to Chromium C++

internal naming, and nothing web-exposed.

entry.title: [accessibility] Decouple PdfOcrController
entry.content:
Teach PdfOcrController to observe whether or not a screen reader is

present or select-to-speak is enabled so that various other bits of the

browser don't need to understand its internal logic. In this change:



- ProfileImpl creates its PdfOcrController during initialization.

ChromeContentBrowserClient no longer needs to know to create it under

specific conditions.

- PdfOcrController observes changes to the process-wide AXMode and

refreshes its state when kScreenReader is added. BrowserView no longer

needs to know to do this.

- PdfOcrController observes status updates published by

AccessibilityManager and refreshes its state when spoken feedback or

select-to-speak are toggled. AccessibilityManager no longer needs to

know to do this.

- EmbeddedA11yManagerLacros now waits until it receives a value for the

kAccessibilityPdfOcrAlwaysActive pref from Ash before it starts

sending a value to profiles.

entry.title: Limit requests to a predefined timeout in the Autofill download manager
entry.content:
Autofill download manager relied on system timeout for requests to

content-autofill.google.com. However, this timeout varies from system

to system, and there are no guarantees that it's reasonably low. There

is no reason to wait more than 10s for a server response; it's highly

likely a packet was lost in a black hole.



It might help in cases with low connectivity like this

https://uma.googleplex.com/p/chrome/timeline_v2?sid=24f05272196ca130a69752628fea97df

as well as for mobile networks with low signal levels. In such cases,

we'll have another try to query the server within the max backoff

duration.



Tested: pointed requests to a non-existent host in my network

(e.g., 10.0.0.8) and dropped outgoing packets to simulate a blackhole.



```

iptables -I OUTPUT -d 10.0.0.8 -j DROP

```

and requests finish within the specified timeout instead of system one.

entry.title: Stop checking "expires" option in Use-As-Dictionary response header
entry.content:
Currently Chromium is using "expires" option in Use-As-Dictionary

response header for the dictionary lifetime. The option name has been

renamed to "ttl" in the spec discussed in IETF HTTPWG.



And the new change in the spac [1] removed this, and the lifetime should

be calculated from the response's freshness [2].



After this CL, when V2 backend is enabled, Chromium will not check

"expires" option, and it will check the response's freshness.



[1]: https://github.com/httpwg/http-extensions/pull/2709

[2]: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9111#name-freshness

entry.title: Check Content-Dictionary header when V2 backend is enabled.
entry.content:
A new "Content-Dictionary" response header was introduced by this spec

change [1].



When V2 backend is enabled, if the "Content-Encoding" response header

indicates that a dictionary is used, Chrome will check the

"Content-Dictionary" response header. And if there is no such header or

it doesn't match with the value of "Available-Dictionary" request

header, Chrome will treat the response as an error.



[1]: https://github.com/httpwg/http-extensions/pull/2680

entry.title: sensors: Support *_ORIENTATION_EULER_ANGLES virtual sensors
entry.content:
This is done entirely at the //services layer. We use the same virtual

sensor type for both Euler angles and quaternions so that the same

virtual sensor type can control both the legacy Device Orientation API

as well as the sensors defined in the Orientation Sensor spec. The trick

is to have one canonical representation internally and convert to and

from it as necessary.



In practice, what we do is only keep *_ORIENTATION_QUATERNION virtual

sensors around in //services, and callers must convert Euler angles to

quaternions first.



From a virtual sensors perspective, the *_ORIENTATION_EULER_ANGLES

sensors are always handled as fusion sensors that take their input data

from an underlying *_ORIENTATION_QUATERNION sensor.



A missing GetMinimumSupportedFrequency() override has been added to

PlatformSensorFusion so that the right value is reported as exercised by

the unit tests.



The existing web tests will be converted in a separate CL, as the

required changes are considerable.

so that forms are ordered by the alphabetically smallest rendered

string.
